<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/KGHNYLGB>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "A Drum’s Trans-Atlantic Journey from Africa to the Americas and Back after the end of Slavery: Annobonese and Fernandino musical cultures." ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=KGHNYLGB> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:KGHNYLGB" ;
  schema:description "Musical instruments are an intrinsic part of culture accompanying people as an essential fac- torin shaping the identity preserved through memory. In equatorial guinea there are some ethnic and social groups: fang, Bubi, ndowe, etc. It is in relation to the Annobonese and the fernandinosmusical culture, that the concept of “Return trip to Africa” becomes meaning- ful. This paperdiscusses this focusing on instruments such as cumbé, kunkí, and dances such as cumbé or bonkó, which constitute an African legacy that has returned and has become a part of equatorial guinea’s musical culture. The paper’s main point is that the identity given by the African elements has remained active until today." ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2010" ;
  schema:publisher "African Sociological Review / Revue Africaine de Sociologie" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.4314/asr.v14i1.70227> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.4314/asr.v14i1.70227" ;
  dcterms:subject "African history and culture studies", "Hispanic-African Historical Relations" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/LG7APPCT>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "Cuban heritage in Africa: Deported Ñáñigos to Fernando Po in the 19th century" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=LG7APPCT> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:LG7APPCT" ;
  schema:description "This paper focuses on the 19th century deportation of Nanigos (members of Abakua, a Cuban secret society) to Fernando Po (Bioko). I argue against the widely held negative image of this group as portrayed in the news and press information in Spanish newspapers from 1865 to 1950 that document the Cuban heritage in Africa. I highlight the point that the deportation of Nanigos to Africa was,in part, due to their association with,in part, due to their association with rebel groups in the decades and years prior to and during the War of Independence. Further, I pointed out the need of the Spanish Government to colonize the African island and use it to harbor expelled groups from the Caribbean island prosecuted for their rebellious character against the colony. As a result, many emancipated slaves1 and Cuban people were deported to Fernando Po in the second half of the nineteenth century, which explains their presence on the island. I discuss, in details, their memory, which has been maintained through some cultural elements - rituals, body attires, and musical and dance elements.. Keywords: Nanigos, slave heritage, Bonko ritual dance, Nankue ritual dance, initiation societies, Cuban deportees" ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2014" ;
  dcterms:subject "Caribbean and African Literature and Culture", "Cuban History and Society", "Hispanic-African Historical Relations" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/99YE3EJ2>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "El sonido del espíritu en las sociedades secretas de África Central" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=99YE3EJ2> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:99YE3EJ2" ;
  schema:description "espanolEl sonido oculto, simboliza el lenguaje del mundo del mas alla en muchas sociedades secretas africanas. La “Voz” del espiritu o “mascara acustica” tiene una emision en dos espacios: el publico y el privado. Investigamos la posible trayectoria de “La Voz” en las sociedades secretas desde Congo a Camerun. Este fenomeno y otros elementos comunes viajarian en el sentido de las migraciones de subgrupos ndowe. El de los balondo, estaria en el origen de la transmision de la “Voz” en Calabar en la sociedad Ekpe, legando la “mascara acustica” a traves de los esclavos carabali a la sociedad secreta Abakua cubana. Encontramos la “Voz” en sociedades secretas ndowe: Ukuku, Mwiri en Gabon; Ngakola en Congo; Bweti, Mweli en Guinea Ecuatorial; Iyengu en Camerun. Indagamos sobre las posibles relaciones etnicas, o una “criollizacion y ritual” en la transmision de “La Voz”, desde la Cuenca del Congo hasta Calabar. EnglishThe hidden sound emitted by an instrument symbolizes the language of the afterlife in many African secret societies. The Voice of the spirit or acoustic mask has an emission in two spaces: public and private. We investigate the possible trajectory of the Voice in secret societies from Congo to Cameroon. This phenomenon and other common elements would travel in the sense of ndowe subgroup migrations. The Balondo ndowe subgroup, would be in the origin of the transmission of the Voice in Calabar in the Ekpe society, transfering the acoustic mask through the carabali slaves to the Cuban Abakua secret society. We find the Voice in many ndowe subgroups in secret societies: Ukuku, Mwiri in Gabon; Ngakola in Congo; Bweti, Mweli in Equatorial Guinea, Iyengu in Cameroon. We inquire about possible ethnic relations, or a cultural and ritual creolization in the transmission of the “Voice, from the Congo Basin to Calabar." ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2017" ;
  schema:publisher "XXII Coloquio de Historia Canario-Americana: las ciudades del mundo Atlántico. Pasado, presente y futuro, 2017" ;
  dcterms:subject "Caribbean and African Literature and Culture", "Hispanic-African Historical Relations", "Linguistic Studies and Language Acquisition" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/XMYU88U5>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "El sonido del espíritu en las sociedades secretas de África Central / The sound of the spirit in the secret societies of Central Africa" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=XMYU88U5> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:XMYU88U5" ;
  schema:description "El sonido oculto, simboliza el lenguaje del mundo del mas alla en muchas sociedades secretas africanas. La “Voz” del espiritu o “mascara acustica” tiene una emision en dos espacios: el publico y el privado. Investigamos la posible trayectoria de “La Voz” en las sociedades secretas desde Congo a Camerun. Este fenomeno y otros elementos comunes viajarian en el sentido de las migraciones de subgrupos ndowe. El de los balondo, estaria en el origen de la transmision de la “Voz” en Calabar en la sociedad Ekpe , legando la “mascara acustica” a traves de los esclavos carabali a la sociedad secreta Abakua cubana. Encontramos la “Voz” en sociedades secretas ndowe: Ukuku, Mwiri en Gabon; Ngakola en Congo; Bweti, Mweli en Guinea Ecuatorial; Iyengu en Camerun. Indagamos sobre las posibles relaciones etnicas, o una “criollizacion y ritual” en la transmision de “La Voz”, desde la Cuenca del Congo hasta Calabar. The hidden sound emitted by an instrument symbolizes the language of the afterlife in many African secret societies. The Voice of the spirit or acoustic mask has an emission in two spaces: public and private. We investigate the possible trajectory of the Voice in secret societies from Congo to Cameroon. This phenomenon and other common elements would travel in the sense of ndowe subgroup migrations. The Balondo ndowe subgroup, would be in the origin of the transmission of the Voice in Calabar in the Ekpe society, transfering the acoustic mask through the carabali slaves to the Cuban Abakua secret society. We find the Voice in many ndowe subgroups in secret societies: Ukuku, Mwiri in Gabon; Ngakola in Congo; Bweti, Mweli in Equatorial Guinea, Iyengu in Cameroon. We inquire about possible ethnic relations, or a cultural and ritual creolization in the transmission of the “Voice, from the Congo Basin to Calabar." ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2016" ;
  schema:publisher "Coloquios de Historia Canario Americana" ;
  dcterms:subject "Caribbean and African Literature and Culture" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/CZY9TH7X>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "La cultura musical Ndowe en el tránsito esclavista del Atlántico. Influencia en la sociedad cubana Abakuá y de vuelta a África, en Guinea Ecuatorial / Ndowe Musical cultura in the Atlantic slave trade. Influence on Cuban society Abakuá and return..." ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=CZY9TH7X> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:CZY9TH7X" ;
  schema:description "El estudio comparativo de los elementos musicales a ambos lados del Atlantico en relacion con la esclavitud, ha generado investigaciones de ida al continente americano, pero apenas hay escritos sobre el viaje de retorno y sus influencias en Africa. En este articulo se analiza el legado cultural de vuelta a traves de la esclavitud del grupo ndowe. Este legado llegado a Cuba con los esclavos carabalies quienes fundan la sociedad Abakua , posteriormente efectua un viaje de retorno a Africa con los deportados abakua llevados a Fernando Poo, hoy en Guinea Ecuatorial. El marco del estudio se situa en una consideracion de las areas culturales en Africa, mas alla de las fronteras coloniales y se inicia una reflexion sobre la busqueda hoy de una identidad mas global en los grupos ndowe y la expresion de una “oralidad secundaria”. El grupo ndowe ocupa hoy un area que se extiende por Gabon, Guinea Ecuatorial, Camerun y parte de Congo. The comparative study of the music on both sides of the Atlantic regarding slavery elements has generated research about the journey to American continent, but there is little written on the return trip and its influences in Africa. In this paper is analyzed the cultural heritage in a back way discussed through slavery of Ndowe group. This legacy arrived in Cuba with Carabalies slaves who founded the society Abakua. Later it was made a return trip to Africa with the deportees Abakua carried to Fernando Poo (today Bioko) in Equatorial Guinea. The framework of the study lies in a consideration of the cultural areas in Africa, beyond the colonial borders and in a reflection on the search nowadays for a more global identity in Ndowe groups and the expression of a “secondary orality” that is starting. The Ndowe group occupies an area extending trough Equatorial Guinea, Cameroon Gabon and some areas in Congo ." ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2014" ;
  schema:publisher "Coloquios de Historia Canario Americana" ;
  dcterms:subject "Cuban History and Society", "Hispanic-African Historical Relations" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/RKEV68GA>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "LA CULTURA MUSICAL NDOWE EN EL TRÁNSITO ESCLAVISTA DEL ATLÁNTICO. INFLUENCIA EN LA SOCIEDAD CUBANA ABAKUÁ Y DE VUELTA A ÁFRICA, EN GUINEA ECUATORIAL NDOWE MUSICAL CULTURE IN THE ATLANTIC SLAVE TRADE. INFLUENCE ON CUBAN SOCIETY ABAKUÁ AND RETURN TO AFRICA IN EQUATORIAL GUINEA" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=RKEV68GA> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:RKEV68GA" ;
  schema:description "The comparative study of the music on both sides of the Atlantic regarding slavery elements has gener - ated research about the journey to American continent, but there is little written on the return trip and its influ- ences in Africa. In this paper is analyzed the cultural heritage in a back way discussed through slavery of Ndowe group. This legacy arrived in Cuba with Carabalies slaves who founded the society Abakua. Later it was made a return trip to Africa with the deportees Abakua carried to Fernando Poo (today Bioko) in Equatorial Guinea. The framework of the study lies in a consideration of the cultural areas in Africa, beyond the colonial borders and in a reflection on the search nowadays for a more global identity in Ndowe groups and the expression of a secondary orality that is starting. The Ndowe group occupies an area extending trough Equatorial Guinea, Cameroon Gabon and some areas in Congo." ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2016" ;
  dcterms:subject "Hispanic-African Historical Relations", "Media, Journalism, and Communication History", "Spanish Literature and Culture Studies" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/G467Q3IC>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "La cultura musical Ndowe en el tránsito esclavista del Atlántico.: Influencia en la sociedad cubana Abakuá y de vuelta a África, en Guinea Ecuatorial" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=G467Q3IC> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:G467Q3IC" ;
  schema:description "espanolEl estudio comparativo de los elementos musicales a ambos lados del Atlantico en relacion con la esclavitud, ha generado investigaciones de ida al continente americano, pero apenas hay escritos sobre el viaje de retorno y sus influencias en Africa. En este articulo se analiza el legado cultural de vuelta a traves de la esclavitud del grupo ndowe. Este legado llegado a Cuba con los esclavos carabalies quienes fundan la sociedad Abakua, posteriormente efectua un viaje de retorno a Africa con los deportados abakua llevados a Fernando Poo, hoy en Guinea Ecuatorial. El marco del estudio se situa en una consideracion de las areas culturales en Africa, mas alla de las fronteras coloniales y se inicia una reflexion sobre la busqueda hoy de una identidad mas global en los grupos ndowe y la expresion de una “oralidad secundaria”. El grupo ndowe ocupa hoy un area que se extiende por Gabon, Guinea Ecuatorial, Camerun y parte de Congo. EnglishThe comparative study of the music on both sides of the Atlantic regarding slavery elements has generated research about the journey to American continent, but there is little written on the return trip and its influences in Africa. In this paper is analyzed the cultural heritage in a back way discussed through slavery of Ndowe group. This legacy arrived in Cuba with Carabalies slaves who founded the society Abakua. Later it was made a return trip to Africa with the deportees Abakua carried to Fernando Poo (today Bioko) in Equatorial Guinea. The framework of the study lies in a consideration of the cultural areas in Africa, beyond the colonial borders and in a reflection on the search nowadays for a more global identity in Ndowe groups and the expression of a “secondary orality” that is starting. The Ndowe group occupies an area extending trough Equatorial Guinea, Cameroon Gabon and some areas in Congo." ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2016" ;
  schema:publisher "Dialnet (Universidad de la Rioja)" ;
  dcterms:subject "Hispanic-African Historical Relations" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/93PUVSID>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "Los tambores ñáñigos en el Museo Nacional (Madrid). La sociedad cubana secreta Abakuá y las trayectoriasen el Atlántico negro" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=93PUVSID> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:93PUVSID" ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2015" ;
  dcterms:subject "Cuban History and Society", "Spanish Literature and Culture Studies" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/IAIZRMIP>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "Los tambores ñáñigos en el Museo Nacional de Antropología (Madrid): la sociedad cubana secreta Abakuá y las trayectorias en el Atlántico negro" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=IAIZRMIP> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:IAIZRMIP" ;
  schema:description "espanolDos de los tambores nanigos (ekue y bonko enchemiya), expuestos hoy en la Sala de America del Museo Nacional de Antropologia, son objetos rituales incautados a la sociedad secreta Abakua en Cuba. Su itinerario hasta el Museo Biblioteca de Ultramar de Madrid en 1889, se situa en un contexto social y politico en los anos previos a la independencia cubana, con detenciones, incautaciones y deportaciones de los denominados entonces nanigos (miembros de la sociedad Abakua). Su exhibicion en el museo en esos anos tuvo consecuencias en los futuros estudios academicos que se han realizado sobre esta asociacion religiosa afrocubana hasta hoy. La sociedad Abakua recrea la sociedad Ekpe de Calabar (Nigeria/Camerun) llevada a Cuba por los esclavos carabali. Muchos deportados nanigos llevaron de vuelta esta memoria africana a Fernando Poo (Guinea Ecuatorial). Iniciamos una reflexion sobre la aportacion desde Calabar del grupo ndowe, con subgrupos etnicos en Guinea Ecuatorial, Camerun y Gabon, en un complejo entramado de trayectorias en el Atlantico negro. EnglishThe two drums of the Nanigos (the ekue and the bonko enchemiya), exposed in the America Hall of the Museo Nacional de Antropologia are ritual objects seized from the secret society Abakua in Cuba. The itinerary to the Museo Biblioteca de Ultramar in 1889 in Madrid is situated in a social and political context in the years before the Cuban independence, with arrests, seizures and deportations of so-called Nanigos (members of Abakua society). Their exhibition at this Museum at that time had an impact on future academic studies that have been done about this Afro-Cuban religious association until nowadays. The Abakua secret society has recreated the Ekpe society in Calabar (Nigeria / Cameroon) brought to Cuba by Calabar slaves. Many Nanigos deportees brought back this memory to Africa to the island of Fernando Poo (Equatorial Guinea). We started a reflection on the contribution from Calabar to Cuba from the Ndowe group, a community with ethnic subgroups in Equatorial Guinea, Cameroon and Gabon in a complex network of paths on the Black Atlantic." ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2015" ;
  schema:publisher "Anales del Museo Nacional de Antropología" ;
  dcterms:subject "Cuban History and Society", "Hispanic-African Historical Relations" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/4C8UTV46>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "Presencia de la sociedad abakuá en Fernando Poo a finales del siglo XIX. Deportados ñáñigos cubanos en la prensa española / Presence of the Abakuá society in Fernando Poo at the end of the 19th Century. Deported Cuban ñañigos in the Spanish press" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=4C8UTV46> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:4C8UTV46" ;
  schema:description "En este articulo constatamos en Fernando Poo(Bioko), la presencia de los nanigos (miembros de lasociedad secreta cubana Abakua), a traves de la prensadecimononica. El bonko o nankue, rito-danza de loscriollos fernandinos analizado en un trabajo anterior,refleja el legado abakua, confirmado ahora en elarchivo escrito. De 1862 a 1897 se enviaron cubanosemancipados y deportados a Fernando Poo. En estetrabajo documentamos las deportaciones realizadas afinal de siglo XIX desde Cuba, con cientos de nanigoshacia Fernando Poo, pasando por Cadiz y Canarias. Laprimera logia abakua en Cuba se funda en 1836,siendo esta sociedad objeto de represion durante lacolonia y la republica. Una de las consecuencias serasu deportacion. La influencia abakua en Biokoconstituye la afirmacion de su identidad y el reflejo deuna memoria conservada como forma de resistencia,suponiendo un legado de ida y vuelta de la riquezacultural africana. In this article we confirm the presence of nanigos(members of Abakua, a Cuban secret society) inFernando Poo (Bioko), through the press in nineteenthcentury. The Bonko or Nankue, a ritual-dance amongFernandino Creoles, analyzed in a previous work,reflects the Abakua legacy now confirmed in thewritten archive. From 1862 to 1897, emancipated anddeported Cubans were sent to Fernando Poo. In thispaper we document the deportations carried out by theend of the nineteenth century, with hundreds ofnanigos leaving Cuba to Fernando Poo, passingthrough Cadiz and the Canary Islands. The firstAbakua juego (lodge) was founded in Cuba in 1836,and this society was repressed during the colonial andrepublican periods. One consequence was deportation.The Abakua influence in Bioko is asserting its identityand reflects their memory preserved as a form ofresistance, assuming a return of a legacy of Africancultural wealth." ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2012" ;
  schema:publisher "Coloquios de Historia Canario Americana" ;
  dcterms:subject "Cuban History and Society", "Hispanic-African Historical Relations", "Spanish Literature and Culture Studies" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/HGYWIJ9C>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "Presencia de la sociedad abakuá en Fernando Poo a finales del siglo XIX: Deportados ñáñigos cubanos en la prensa española" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=HGYWIJ9C> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:HGYWIJ9C" ;
  schema:description "espanolEn este articulo2 constatamos en Fernando Poo (Bioko), la presencia de los nanigos (miembros de la sociedad secreta cubana Abakua), a traves de la prensa decimononica. El bonko o nankue, rito-danza de los criollos fernandinos analizado en un trabajo anterior, refleja el legado abakua, confirmado ahora en el archivo escrito. De 1862 a 1897 se enviaron cubanos emancipados y deportados a Fernando Poo. En este trabajo documentamos las deportaciones realizadas a final de siglo XIX desde Cuba, con cientos de nanigos hacia Fernando Poo, pasando por Cadiz y Canarias. La primera logia abakua en Cuba se funda en 1836, siendo esta sociedad objeto de represion durante la colonia y la republica. Una de las consecuencias sera su deportacion. La influencia abakua en Bioko constituye la afirmacion de su identidad y el reflejo de una memoria conservada como forma de resistencia, suponiendo un legado de ida y vuelta de la riqueza cultural africana. EnglishIn this article we confirm the presence of nanigos (members of Abakua, a Cuban secret society) in Fernando Poo (Bioko), through the press in nineteenth century. The Bonko or Nankue, a ritual-dance among Fernandino Creoles, analyzed in a previous work, reflects the Abakua legacy now confirmed in the written archive. From 1862 to 1897, emancipated and deported Cubans were sent to Fernando Poo. In this paper we document the deportations carried out by the end of the nineteenth century, with hundreds of nanigos leaving Cuba to Fernando Poo, passing through Cadiz and the Canary Islands. The first Abakua juego (lodge) was founded in Cuba in 1836, and this society was repressed during the colonial and republican periods. One consequence was deportation. The Abakua influence in Bioko is asserting its identity and reflects their memory preserved as a form of resistance, assuming a return of a legacy of African cultural wealth." ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2014" ;
  schema:publisher "Dialnet (Universidad de la Rioja)" ;
  dcterms:subject "Caribbean and African Literature and Culture", "Cuban History and Society", "Hispanic-African Historical Relations" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/YJT48ZMR>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "Trayectorias e identidades en el diálogo Atlántico más allá de las fronteras coloniales: instrumentos de la sociedad cubana Abakuá en el Museo Nacional de Antropología de Madrid" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=YJT48ZMR> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:YJT48ZMR" ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2018" ;
  schema:publisher "Dialnet (Universidad de la Rioja)" ;
  dcterms:subject "Cuban History and Society" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/CAYG7WE2>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "Presencia de la Sociedad Abakuá en Fernando Poo a finales del siglo XIX. Deportados ñáñigos cubanos en la prensa española" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=CAYG7WE2> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:CAYG7WE2" ;
  schema:description "En este articulo constatamos en Fernando Poo (hoy Bioko), la presencia de los nanigos (miembros de la sociedad secreta Abakua), a traves de la prensa decimononica. De 1862 a 1897 se enviaron cubanos emancipados y deportados a Fernando Poo con cientos de nanigos entre ellos. Esta sociedad fue objeto de represion durante la colonia y la republica y una de las consecuencias sera su deportacion. La influencia abakua en El Bonko o Nankue, rito-danza de los criollos fernandinos constituye la afirmacion de su identidad, el reflejo de una memoria conservada como forma de resistencia, suponiendo un legado de ida y vuelta de la riqueza cultural africana." ;
  schema:author "Isabela de Aranzadi Pérez" ;
  schema:datePublished "2015" ;
  schema:publisher "Batey. Revista Cubana de Antropología Sociocultural (ISSN 2225-529X)" ;
  dcterms:subject "Caribbean and African Literature and Culture", "Cuban History and Society", "Hispanic-African Historical Relations" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/5JRTNG8Z>
  a schema:Chapter ;
  schema:name ". Arrival" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=5JRTNG8Z> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:5JRTNG8Z" ;
  schema:description "This chapter is based largely on Abakuá narratives about the arrival of Carabalá Ékpè members and the various stages in their process of recreating Ékpè in Cuba. They created the first Abakuá lodges and established the three major “ethnic” lineages: Efí, Efó, and Orú. Most of the Abakuá language used to tell this story is contained in chants used even today in ceremonies." ;
  schema:author "Ivor L. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2009" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0002> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0002" ;
  dcterms:subject "Cuban History and Society" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/M93AUQIH>
  a schema:Chapter ;
  schema:name ". Conclusions" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=M93AUQIH> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:M93AUQIH" ;
  schema:description "Abstract This chapter summarizes the preceding discussions, which showed how African migrants in colonial Cuba, through Abakuá, reorganized their homeland government and passed it onto their offspring in the form of a mutual aid society. Abakuá expanded its urban networks through the interactions of many communities, including African nation-groups, free black artisans, the black and mulatto militias, urban fugitives, and African descendants from Spain. Abakuá groups also functioned as antislavery cells that maintained a sense of morality and history among their communities." ;
  schema:author "Ivor L. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2009" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0009> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0009" ;
  dcterms:subject "Colonialism, slavery, and trade", "Cuban History and Society", "Historical Studies in Central America" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/9HMVLEJZ>
  a schema:Chapter ;
  schema:name ". Disintegration of the Spanish Empire" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=9HMVLEJZ> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:9HMVLEJZ" ;
  schema:description "This chapter reviews the last two decades of colonial rule, including the official termination of the African cabildos de nación, their Three Kings’ Day processions in Havana, and the attempts by police to destroy Abakuá by confiscating their sacred objects. In the emergent Cuban popular theater and music there is evidence of Abakuá used as a symbol of cubanía (Cuban-ness). To illustrate contemporary anecdotes gathered about Abakuá and African-descended General Antonio Maceo, the chapter reviews the significance of Maceo, whose mother is regarded as the “mother of the Cuban nation”." ;
  schema:author "Ivor L. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2009" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0007> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0007" ;
  dcterms:subject "Cuban History and Society" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/V8LYB2MK>
  a schema:Chapter ;
  schema:name ". Dispersal" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=V8LYB2MK> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:V8LYB2MK" ;
  schema:description "This chapter describes how Abakué was made illegal in 1875, with its members (as well as other anticolonials) dispersed to Spanish penal colonies in North and West Africa. Those who could escaped from Cuba to Florida to join the emerging cigar industry. Responding to scholarship that argues for the recreation of Abakuá lodges in exile, having learned otherwise from Abakuá leaders, the chapter discusses issues basic to the process, which highlight the extraordinary achievements of Abakuá’s foundation in Cuba." ;
  schema:author "Ivor L. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2009" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0006> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0006" ;
  dcterms:subject "Colonialism, slavery, and trade" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/LDADYYKY>
  a schema:Chapter ;
  schema:name ". Havana Is the Key" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=LDADYYKY> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:LDADYYKY" ;
  schema:description "A profound relationship exists between Abakuá and Cuban popular music. This chapter lays out evidence for Calabarí presence in the formation of rumba music in the nineteenth century and the use of clave sticks in the rumba and son genres. It also describes how Abakuá composers have consistently recorded their social and ritual history using Abakuá language as well as rhythms and distinctive sounds in commercial recordings." ;
  schema:author "Ivor L. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2009" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0008> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0008" ;
  dcterms:subject "Cuban History and Society" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/75F4QC2L>
  a schema:Chapter ;
  schema:name ". Planting Abakuá in Cuba, 1830s to 1860s" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=75F4QC2L> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:75F4QC2L" ;
  schema:description "This chapter uses the concept of planting, of activating the brotherhood—shared by Ékpè and Abakuá—to describe how Abakuá expanded from the 1830s to 1860s in a cosmopolitan urban environment, and in the face of repression as experienced in the wake of the infamous Conspiracy of La Escalera in the 1840s. Documenting the process of the transmission of Ékpè into Cuba, the chapter lists the major lodges founded and identifies their possible Cross River precedents. In the 1860s, Abakuá expanded into the nearby port city of Matanzas, with the sponsorship of Havana lodges." ;
  schema:author "Ivor L. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2009" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0004> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0004" ;
  dcterms:subject "Cuban History and Society" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/QNUU9ZMT>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "A Secret Society Goes Public: The Relationship between Abakua and Cuban Popular Culture" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=QNUU9ZMT> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:QNUU9ZMT" ;
  schema:description "eties of the Cross River region. It was founded in Havana, Cuba, in 1836 to resist slavery, and has since been active in many aspects of Cuban culture. Although her-metic and little known even within Cuba, an analysis of Cuban popular music recorded from the 1920s until the present reveals Abakua influence in nearly every genre of Cuban popular music. Abakua lore is orally transmitted, and Cuban musi-cians who are Abakua members have continually documented key aspects of their society&amp;apos;s history in commercial recordings, often in Abakua language. Because theirs is a secret language for initiates only, Abakua have commercially recorded actual chants of the society, knowing that outsiders cannot interpret them. Even so, these recordings have been very popular because the Abakua represent a rebel-lious, even anticolonial, aspect of Cuban culture. Now played throughout the Amer-icas, Mrica, Europe, and Asia, Cuban popular music and its derivatives maintain Abakua language and aesthetics as integral elements. Because so little has been written about the society by members themselves, commercial recordings with Abakua content are an important source of knowledge about this group. While lis-tening to the lyrics, I realized that Abakua musicians have sung about their contri-butions to Cuban history, their liberation struggles, and race relations. My research suggests the rising importance of Abakua as a symbol of Cuban culture. Resume: La Societe des hommes Abakua tire son origine des Societes Ekpe ouest africaines de la region de Cross River. Elle fut fondee a Havane a Cuba en 1836 pour resister al&amp;apos;esclavage et est depuis active dans bien des aspects de la culture cubaine. Bien qu&amp;apos;elle reste hermetique et peu connue meme al&amp;apos;interieurde Cuba," ;
  schema:author "Ivor L. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2000" ;
  schema:publisher "African Studies Review" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.2307/524726> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.2307/524726" ;
  dcterms:subject "Caribbean and African Literature and Culture", "Caribbean history, culture, and politics", "Cuban History and Society" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/JSH5B2GI>
  a schema:Chapter ;
  schema:name "Abakuá" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=JSH5B2GI> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:JSH5B2GI" ;
  schema:description "Abstract This chapter explores Abakuá’s secret society, which had been fundamental in the formation of Cuban national identity. It explains how Abakuá lodges were necessarily created in secrecy due to being persecuted by colonial authorities before the adaptation of Abakuá to the Cuban context. Moreover, Abakuá exemplifies the concept of los cimarrones urbanos, which refers to urban underground fugitives from the cultural system of the colonizer. Abakuá tradition is an important example of established alternatives to assimilation to Western cultural norms. The chapter explains that Abakuá defended an autonomous and collective identity based upon an ancestral heritage that the dominant class persistently tried to abolish." ;
  schema:author "Ivor L. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2024" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780190916961.013.7> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.1093/oxfordhb/9780190916961.013.7" ;
  dcterms:subject "Cuban History and Society" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/IDEDRSSK>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "Bongó Itá: leopard society music and language in West Africa, Western Cuba, and New York City" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=IDEDRSSK> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:IDEDRSSK" ;
  schema:description "The Abakuá mutual-aid society of Cuba, recreated from the Ékpè leopard society of West Africa's Cross River basin, is a richly detailed example of African cultural transmission to the Americas. Its material culture, such as masquerades and drum construction, as well as rhythmic structures, are largely based on Ékpè models. Its ritual language is expressed through hundreds of chants that identify source regions and historical events; many can be interpreted by speakers of Èfìk, the pre-colonial lingua franca of the Cross River region (Miller 2005). With the help of both Ékpè and Abakuá leaders, I have examined relationships between the musical practices of West African Ékpè, Cuban Abakuá, as well as Cuban migrants to the United States whose commercial recordings have evoked West African places and events historically relevant to Abakuá, meanwhile contributing to the evolution of North American jazz." ;
  schema:author "Ivor L. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2011" ;
  schema:publisher "African and Black Diaspora An International Journal" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.1080/17528631.2012.629437> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.1080/17528631.2012.629437" ;
  dcterms:subject "Caribbean and African Literature and Culture", "Caribbean history, culture, and politics", "Hispanic-African Historical Relations" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/8C7BRIYB>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "Cuban Abakuá Chants: Examining New Linguistic and Historical Evidence for the African Diaspora" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=8C7BRIYB> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:8C7BRIYB" ;
  schema:description "Abstract: The Cuban Abakuá society—derived from the Èfik Ékpè and Ejagham Úgbè societies of southeastern Nigeria and southwestern Cameroon—was founded in Havana in the 1830s by captured leaders of Cross River villages. This paper examines the process by which West African Ékpè members were able to understand contemporary Cuban Abakuá chants, and indicates how these texts may be used as historical documents. This methodology involves first recording and interpreting Abakuá chants with Cuban elders, and then interpreting these same chants with the aid of West African Èfik speakers. The correlation of data in these chants with those in documents created by Europeans and Africans from the eighteenth to twentieth centuries indicates a vocabulary that includes many geographic and ethnic names and an occasional historical figure. These examples may lead to a reevaluation of the extent to which African identity and culture were transmitted during the transAtlantic diaspora. Abakuá intellectuals have used commercial recordings to extol their history and ritual lineages. Evidence indicates that Cuban Abakuá identity is based on detailed knowledge of ritual lineages stemming from specific locations in their homelands, and not upon a vague notion of an African “national” or “ethnic” identity. The persistence of the Abakuá society contradicts the official construction of a Cuban national identity." ;
  schema:author "Ivor L. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2005" ;
  schema:publisher "African Studies Review" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.1353/arw.2005.0030> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.1353/arw.2005.0030" ;
  dcterms:subject "Caribbean history, culture, and politics", "Cuban History and Society", "Race, History, and American Society" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/8PNBJB8G>
  a schema:Chapter ;
  schema:name "Cubans in Calabar: Ékpè Has One Voice" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=8PNBJB8G> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:8PNBJB8G" ;
  schema:description "This epilogue describes an encounter of Abakuá and Ékpè in Calabar at the International Ékpè Festival in 2004. This event greatly impacted Abakuá and Ékpè groups, who are confirming their local history through the practice of their counterparts." ;
  schema:author "Ivor L. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2009" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0010> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.14325/mississippi/9781934110836.003.0010" ;
  dcterms:subject "African history and culture studies", "Cuban History and Society", "Race, History, and American Society" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/FEH9BKW7>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "Elephant and Leopard Symbols in the Cross River Region and Its Caribbean Diaspora" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=FEH9BKW7> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:FEH9BKW7" ;
  schema:description "Throughout West Africa’s Cross River basin, regional identities developed in recent centuries through trade exchanges among small forest-dwelling communities, from the foothills of the Bamenda Highlands to the port of Calabar (Fig. 1). In the process, the Ékpè “leopard” society was established as the community police of the region, each “principality” having its own lodge (Miller 2009; Miller and Ojong 2012).2 At the top of the food chain, the leopard served as metaphor for the ideal consciousness of a council of titleholders, whose collective decisions were the final say in community matters. Like the solitary leopard, Ékpè titleholders were expected to be cautious and observant to detect antisocial behavior, and to pounce rapidly in resolving problems through council decisions.Elephants also served as metaphors for leadership; described as “monsters of the land,” they represented an awesome power within the forest.3 Since elephants move in herds, lineage heads displayed their tusks as a symbol of their ability to unify their people. Carved elephant tusk horns signaled paternal authority; elephant tail hairs inserted into caps identified lineage leadership, and elephant images performed in communal rites emphasized the immensity of a ritual investiture. In all cases, these symbols used in ceremony informed local deities and ancestors that a consecrated lineage head was requesting their support on behalf of the community.The leopard, elephant, and other animals are believed to have a spiritual avatar. These “mystic” animals participate in royal investitures and proclamations: Ékpè initiations are authorized through the resounding “voice of the leopard,” while important events are proclaimed when a tusk trumpet is blown to produce “the voice of the elephant.”4 These reverberations alert the entire community, which includes the living, the deities of the territory under their jurisdiction, and the ancestors buried there, as in the example from Úrúán in Figure 2.5Available evidence suggests that in the distant past these symbols emerged as totems for migrating kin-groups or lineages. Lévi-Strauss linked totemism to regimes of hunting/gathering or “shifting cultivation,” where foraging terrain and/or gardening plots rotate every few years and the residence adapts accordingly.6 In the Upper Cross River, Idoma prehistory of the sixteenth-nineteenth centuries fits this template: “The examination of totems has emerged as one of the new methodological devices for the historian of pre-colonial Africa” (Erim 1978: 56, following Webster 1975). Kindreds were differentiated from each other by observing “an iho (an animal forbiddance)”; for example: “all the kindred groups which observe the ogonopo fish totem are descended from a common ancestor, Ode,” even if they became geographically scattered (Erim 1978: 61).Early twentieth century reports by British colonists in the Calabar region contain garbled hints of totemic organization, which Amaury Talbot perceived as the historical origin of a regional club7:When settlements became permanent and fostered heritable land claims, totems were repurposed as political symbols as in regional multiethnic institutions like Ékpè and the Njoku Malé “elephant medicine” society, described below.8As Old Calabar became a major Atlantic port through contact with European traders, captive humans, elephant tusks, and other forest products were dispersed across the Atlantic world. Carved elephant tusks that entered Europe from the 1500s onwards are maintained in museum collections. In the Calabar region elephant tusks are inherited as royal property within lineages, while in the Caribbean the Cuban descendants of Africans maintain elephant and leopard symbols within initiation lineages as emblematic of their African heritage, specifically the Ocha and Ifá systems of the Lukumí (Yorùbá) and Arará (Fon) as well as the Abakuá mutual aid society derived from the Ékpè institution of the Cross River region, as discussed below.9Both the African Forest Elephant (Loxodonta cyclotis) and Leopard (Panthera pardus) are native to the entire forest belt of Atlantic Africa (from Senegal to Angola).10 The earliest evidence of elephants and leopards as royal symbols in southeastern Nigeria was dated to the ninth century; southeast of Onitcha, the Ìgbò Úkwú royal burial site included three ivory tusks, as well as bronze pendants of an elephant head, a leopard’s head, and a shell surmounted by a leopard (Shaw 1973: 18; 1970: 68, fig. 14).Portuguese merchant navigators visiting the Gulf of Guinea brought elephant tusks into Europe in the 1500s, and cartographers began to identify Africa with elephants.11 A map produced in 1636 in Amsterdam shows elephants in “Biafara” (later called “Biafra”), which includes the Cross River region (Fig. 3).Early traffickers referred to captive Africans as “black ivories,” while trading firearms, gunpowder, alcohol, and textiles for ivory tusks and humans (Ardener 2001: 128, 130.) An elephant with a howdah is central to the coat of arms of the Royal African Company, established in 1660 by London merchants.12 Both ivories and humans were documented in trade reports from the Calabar region by D.P. Pereira (Portuguese, 1506), O. Dapper (Dutch, 1668), and J. Barbot (French, 1678 onwards):As African ivories and captive Africans entered Lisbon, by 1550, 10% of the population of Lisbon and other towns were West and Central Africans (Saunders 1982: xi, 7, 13, 15-16, 20-21, 54-55).13 Shipping records document trade in ivories and humans over the centuries: for example, the French ship La Pourvoyance, laden with a cargo of slaves and 500 pounds of ivory, was captured in 1793 by John Tobin of Liverpool, master of the privateer Gipsy (Latham (1974: 863). The exchange of enslaved people for “36 Elephants Teeth” was documented in the 1784 voyage of the Golden Age from Badagry to Jamaica (Lovejoy 2018: 47).14 Some ivory entered the Caribbean, as an 1835 Havana court case documented an African cabildo “nation group” in possession of “a piece of elephant tusk with two faces engraved in it [that] serves as a small bell to call to God” (Lovejoy 2018: 91). Elephant and even leopard ivory has ever remained an important heritage symbol for Afro-Caribbean people, as we will see.Carved elephant ivory horns in European collections were identified by Ezio Bassani as arriving from “1551-1600.” He concluded they were from the Calabar region, and “carved in one workshop … between the end of the sixteenth and the middle of the seventeenth centuries” (Bassani 2000: 266).15 Bassani based his analysis on carving styles and symbols, mainly crocodile or tortoise forms used today on the coded ùkárá cloth used in the Ékpè “leopard” society (see Fig. 13).16 These symbols were also carved into elephant tusks in the Grassfields region of Cameroon, as Chris Geary observed: “In design, these tusks [display] … icons common in the Grassfields repertoire… . the outer bands of rainbow lizard and elephant allude to royal power …” (Geary 1992: 235). Locals view the animals displayed on the royal cloth and tusks of this region as messengers of the deities that support the investiture of lineage heads.Having summarized the known history of elephant tusk and leopard symbols in Calabar and its hinterlands, the following presents the author’s research findings in several communities that display them in rites and royal dress.From Benin City to the west and the Cross River region to the east, both elephant and leopard symbols are displayed in contemporary royal procedures (Fig. 4). The ubiquity of ivory sumptuary goods across the West African forest zone, including bracelets, anklets, and trumpets as well as tusks on ancestral shrines, bespeaks their central role as signs of wealth, privilege, and political authority. Some of these uses were also tied to ritualized hunting, symbolizing the prestige of preagricultural social organization and its importance in many local institutions of chieftaincy. The nearly total recent disappearance of elephant and leopard populations across the region renders this powerful ecological-political prehistory less visible to outside visitors, but it remains vivid in folk memory and visible in sumptuary regalia as in these examples.The Bangwa of Fontem, Cameroon, were a trade link between the Cross River region and the Grasslands. Robert Brain learned in the 1960s that Bangwa “patrilineal as well as matrilineal ancestors are worshipped through their successors who are the custodians of the ancestral skulls” (Brain 1972: 107).In Fontem in the early twenty-first century, elephant and leopard symbols were paramount during the investiture of a village head as an Ékpè titleholder. After his training and consecration by elders in the nearby sacred forest grove, the village head led several processions from the grove to his compound; the third featured a mobile “house” representing a “spiritual elephant” draped in the ndop cloth of the Grassfields region (Fig. 5).17This village head, Mr. Philip Tazi (a.k.a. Sisiku Mbe Tazi Ate’awung IX) describes the third procession:Elephant hair caps are a corresponding royal symbol used by lineage heads. Their use extends to Bangwa and Manyu in Cameroon and to Éjághám-speaking communities in eastern Nigeria (“Ekoi” on colonial maps; for details see Geary 1992: 230 figs. 11–13, and Notué and Triaca 2005: 178). In Íkóm, a Clan Head wears an inherited elephant hair cap (Fig. 6). In the same community, the façade of an Ékpè hall displays a painted elephant (Fig. 7).Among Ngóló-speaking people in South West Cameroon, a village council consulted the oracle before commencing an Ékpè event, which responded positively. In response, the overall head of local traditional societies blew an inherited elephant tusk horn—which he claimed to be centuries old—to herald the blessing of the ancestors and deities of the land. (Fig. 8).21After this affirmation, an Njoku Malé “elephant medicine” mask emerged from the forest through a spiritually protective gateway (Fig. 9), then moved throughout the village to purify the space (Fig. 10), and finally entered the Ékpè hall (Fig. 11). Njoku Malé is a royal initiation club represented by body-masks. Edwin Ardener reported:Indigo-dyed ùkárá cloth is used exclusively by Ékpè society members. Eli Bentor documented ùkárá cloths made by contractors from Arochukwu communities, while Ábíríbá (phonetic spelling “Ébíríbá”) locals also claim that workshops operated in their communities (Fig. 12) (Bentor 2015).23 Produced in Ábíríbá decades ago, a rare cloth portrays an elephant, leopard, frog, turtle, crayfish, and crab as messengers of the deities of the land and water evoked by Ékpè initiates (Fig. 13).24 Another rare example featuring an elephant form was used as the backdrop for a Clan Head’s throne in Calabar (Fig. 14).Among the Yakurr people of Ugep, each head of a paternal family possesses an elephant tusk horn. During important events, a family head will appear holding a staff while his assistant blows an elephant tusk horn (Fig. 15).25 From this community, Dr. Otu Abam Ubi explains:In the port city of Calabar, Èfịk-speaking clans are organized into a dozen houses, derived from the trading “canoe-houses” of the seventeenth through nineteenth centuries (Dike 1956: 34; Miller 2009: 76). During annual celebrations, Cobham House is represented by banner featuring a portrait of founding ancestor Éyọ Émà on a throne, wearing a leopard-skin headband with an ivory tusk under each foot (Fig. 16). Èfịk Houses are proud of their centuries of contact with British merchants, reflected in the name Cobham, an anglicized variant of Akabom.27In the same annual celebration, each Èfịk house displayed a representative mask. A crowd-pleaser was the raffia-fiber Íbóm mask with a long “elephant trunk” and two short tusks (Fig. 17). Although Íbóm is not part of the Ékpè society, only Ékpè initiates may act as Íbóm participants, who perform songs and rhythms of the yàkpè Ékpè grade.28 Íbóm performance once again emphasizes interplay between leopard and elephant symbols.Calabar author Bassey Efiong Bassey reported that “an elephant represents Oku Akama,” alluding to the early functions of this Ékpè grade to knock down the thatched dwellings of those who resisted decisions of the council of elders.29 He describes this Ékpè grade as “well equipped for demolition …. Oku Akama is animalistic in form. The Elephant and her baby represent it. This is aptly demonstrated in its dance form” (Fig. 18) (Bassey 2001: 67, 119).30Among the Èfịks of Calabar, Èfé Àsàsbọ (hall of the python), is an Ńdèm shrine where the Èdídèm (sovereign) is invested (Goldie [1862] 1964: 601).31 A selected Ètúbòm “head of House” is first invested here as Èdídèm before receiving a government certificate making him the Obong of Calabar, “the single being who more than any other man united in himself the quintessence and grandeur and, perhaps, sanctity of the Efik tradition” (Hart 1964: 5).32 An enthroned Èdídèm was photographed in 1973 outside the Èfé Àsàsbò with each foot placed upon a nuk-enen “elephant tusk” (Fig. 19).33Calabar indigenes are organized into three historically distinct communities, Èfịk, Efût, and Qua. The secretary of Big Qua Clan, “Èsínjò Ótóè” Èdím Íká Èdím Ìtákpô, spoke about elephant symbols in royal processions of his community (Fig. 20)34:The recent Ndidem (Paramount Ruler and Éjághám Patriarch) of the Quas of Calabar, Patrick I. Oquagbor V, reflected about the leopard skin cap and elephant tusk symbols of his throne:Contemporary royal displays of elephant and leopard symbols derive from a precolonial context irrevocably altered through early trade with Europeans who brought firearms, subsequent colonial administrations that transformed the societies, leading to the widespread loss of local languages, along with destruction of the forest environment. These tragedies are reflected in the transformation of leopard symbols, for example in urban Calabar, where some Ékpè titleholders now claim that ékpè/mgbè means “lion,” and not “leopard,” as established in the historical literature.36 This transformation was visualized in a painting on the Ékpè hall of Ekondo Titi community in Cameroon, known locally as Etana or Mátámò (Fig. 21).37 Here, the painted seal of an Ékpè hall features the symbol of a lion, thus erasing a centuries long tradition of identification with the native Panthera pardus.The contemporary symbol of a lion vs. a leopard indicates several factors: a West African population disconnected from the critically endangered wildlife of their region, the inconsistent translation of local terms into Nigerian Pidgin, the loss of literacy in local languages, and perhaps the persistent prominence of the lion as symbol of British monarchy, as presented on the royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom from 1837 onwards.38In Cuba, the Abakuá mutual aid society—established in Havana in the early 1800s as a variant of Cross River’s Ékpè institution—ritually reproduces “the Voice of the leopard,” while an Abakuá visual arts tradition frequently reproduces leopard images.39 Elephant images and even carved ivory arrived to Cuba in tandem with human trafficking. One Abakuá manuscript reports about West African ivory merchants: “Batanga: Dealer (of petty merchandise and ivory)”—which is corroborated by the diary of Thomas Hutchinson, a British visitor to Batanga (present Kribi, Cameroon) in the late 1850s (Cabrera 2020: 76, 409n71).40 Several Abakuá references to elephants in regards to founding rites in West Africa were documented by folklorist Lydia Cabrera.41 Initiated elders taught her that “in the beginning,” ritual offerings included ivory: “Some spells are done with animal teeth, from mokueriré ndó (elephant), from ngrí (tiger), and also with the teeth of deceased humans” (Cabrera 1988a: 246).42In the 1800s in Havana, an ivory horn was sounded by an Arará (Fon) cabildo “nation group” during funerals and annual processions “celebrated on the day of Easter Pentecost,” exemplifying how Africans adapted their heritage practices to the Cuban context, as reported by Cuban scholar Fernando Ortiz (1955: 334-35).Another West African system recreated in colonial Cuba was Ifá divination. The Ifá oracle sign “Obe Kana” contains a parable of how Orula (deity of divination) used the elephant tusk.43 Lydia Cabrera published a literary version of this legend44:In both West Africa and Cuba, the irọfa or irọke “oracle tapper” is made in the shape of an elephant tusk, while the myth of Ifá’s foundation in West Africa narrates that all parts of the elephant were used.45 Some contemporary Cuban babaláwos possess ivory “oracle tappers” produced in West Africa and gifted from colleagues there (Fig. 22). Elephants are symbols of both Ifá divination and “Òrìṣà funfun” (white deities), specifically Ọbàtálá (Bascom (1969/1991: 185n3).46 In Havana in the decade of 1950, Ortiz reported trumpet made of … among the of the in the of a of the used in ceremony are with that the An elephant in the context of other Ifá oracle symbols was featured on one (Fig. in Havana for and Abakuá this presents the Ifá oracle as an of West African royal the Cross River during the precolonial and other animals appear to have totems for early migrating From the once permanent settlements were established for of the region, the lineage totems their functions to symbols for regional initiation led by royal members. The of West African elephant and leopard symbols is in the Carved tusks Europe as prestige trade goods in the sixteenth and seventeenth some from the Calabar the subsequent of European firearms, elephants and leopards have nearly from Nigeria and their as deities and icons of in heads display inherited elephant tusks and leopard to their tusk trumpets are blown on important by to family are performed under the of the Ékpè “leopard” the captive Africans in the Caribbean taught their descendants and about elephants and leopards central to Cuban initiation known as Ifá and derived from the Ifá oracle system of and the Ékpè society of the Calabar Here, functions as historical memory to identify with a African heritage that into From West the but the the to where both is in the of" ;
  schema:author "Ivor L. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2026" ;
  schema:publisher "African Arts" ;
