tive in Music 2, no. 2 (Fall I974)5i ‘. 111-116. 1973‘ - - - &#39; ‘ - ~ ‘ &#39; &#39; 1: Crew i‘ S , R b t E. World Mum. Mum Umvrrrrc, Mum Mind. Remnmg t o ‘ A; wig; xiii”: Studio in Woodstock, New rm. Ann Arbor: Arborville Publishing, ,, 1996. Todd Loretta. “Aboriginal Narratives in Cyberspace.” In Immersed in Technology: I Lcod) 179-194., Cambridge: MIT Press, 1996- Toop, David. “Music: A Style of No Style That Spurns All Constraints.” New York &#39; Timex, 13 May zoox, 2.219. VVatr0us Peter. “John Zorn Takes Over die Town.” New Erie Times, 24- F€bI&#39;1131&#39;Y I 89,C:23. ZOIII91, Iohn, ed. Arcana: Musicians on Music. New York: Granary B00ll5a 200°- . Kldngijmrrzrt: Wage improvisierrer Musik. Frankfurt am Main: Fisher Ta.s- “ _ Now; 3 Pggggy, A Ngw World Mmic—Crearive Music. New Haven: Kiom. &#39;1‘ Art and Virtual Environmmts, edited by Mary Anne Moser and Douglas Mac-_ - MICHAEL DESSEN Improvismg in or Dz&#39;ﬁ”ermt Clove Steve Coleman and AfroCuba de Matanzas Let me begin by saying that, to some, my notions concerning voice in improvised music may border on the realm of speculation; however, I am suggesting that the door for research is open, To be speciﬁc: one researcher, Mr, Walter]. Ong, a University Professor of Humanities and Psychiatry at St. Louis University in Missouri, has said: “In various parts of the world, new methods of analysis have been developed whose conclusions reveal the limitations of the Anglo—American outlook we inherit.” I once asked the late Io Jones, “What was Lester Young‘s philosophy concerning improvised music?” He promptly replied, qI/ester played his philosophy.” —Yusef Lateef a_’ ‘i Like many of the improviser-composers coming out of African-American _&#39; creative traditions in the late twentieth century, Steve Coleman has been ac- ‘ &#39;3 tive in a wide range of cultural and musical spaces} While known within &#39;1 V the jazz world as a key member of the M—Base collective} Coleman has also &#39; .« collaborated with musi