<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/RITSFVWB>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "El tesoro de los Quimbayas, un siglo después" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=RITSFVWB> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:RITSFVWB" ;
  schema:description "En la region del Quindio, en 1890, cerca del pueblo de Filandia, los guaqueros sacaron un ajuar funerario en oro y ceramica, sepultado entre los siglos II a.c. y X d.c. correspondiente al estilo quimbaya clasico. Por su riqueza, rareza, cantidad y diversidad de objetos rituales o de sus suntuosos atuendos, - exquisitas obras de arte de las mas refinada orfebreria - las 123 piezas de esta ofrenda, constituidas como simbolos religiosos o emblemas jerarquicos precolombinos, son El Tesoro de los Quimbayas. Un siglo despues de su descubrimiento, de haberse expuesto en 1892, durante el IV Centenario de America, en Madrid, y de su donacion a la Corona Espanola, nos proponemos hacer algunos planteamientos sobre estos hechos desde la problematica de identidad y patrimonio cultural." ;
  schema:author "Pablo Gamboa Hinestrosa" ;
  schema:datePublished "1998" ;
  schema:publisher "Ensayos Historia y Teoría del Arte" ;
  dcterms:subject "Archaeology and Cultural Heritage" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/L7S557A4>
  a schema:Thesis ;
  schema:name "The cry of trokosi girls in Ghana. A qualitative study of the trokosi practice in Ghana in light of diakonia and human rights." ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=L7S557A4> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:L7S557A4" ;
  schema:description "Children especially girls are under different types of oppression in Sub-Saharan Africa due\\nto various practices, belief systems, values, and laws. In Ghana, one practice that seems to\\nsubjugate women and girls in particular is the troxorvi system. Troxorvi or trokosi is a\\npractice that involves the acceptance of human being especially virgin girls for the\\natonement of real or alleged misconduct of a family member. The committed girl stays in\\nthe shrine as a “slave” and owes allegiance to the deity for the rest of her life. However,\\ncontemporary societies frown upon and make laws to eradicate any form of slavery due to\\nits human right abuses. In 1998, Ghana amended her laws prohibiting the troxorvi practice\\nas well as committing herself to human rights values by signing most of the international\\nlaws on human rights including those on children and women. After a decade of\\npromulgation of the Law against the troxorvi practice, not even a single culprit has been\\narrested. The study explores the human rights abuses within the troxorvi system and efforts\\nby diaconal actors. It further explores how diakonia could be employed as a\\nmultidimensional approach towards eradication of the troxorvi practice in Ghana." ;
  schema:author "Palma Abla Howusu" ;
  schema:datePublished "2016" ;
  schema:publisher "Duo Research Archive (University of Oslo)" ;
  dcterms:subject "African cultural and philosophical studies", "Homelessness and Social Issues" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/TD4GTWJE>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "A view from itia ororó kande" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=TD4GTWJE> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:TD4GTWJE" ;
  schema:description "The Cuban male esoteric sodality abakuá has long been interpreted as a transatlantically displaced version of the type of secret society known as ekpe or ngbe in the Cross-River region of south-eastern Nigeria and south-western Cameroon. While not disputing such attributions of African origins, this essay seeks to trace the contours of an alternative history of abakuá. My aim is to confront \"objectivist\" accounts of the diffusionary history of ekpe and abakuá with the ways in which contemporary members of Cuban abakuá ritually produce relations to an African past which they create by performing it into being in the New World present. © 2006 European Association of Social Anthropologists." ;
  schema:author "Palmié, Stephan" ;
  schema:datePublished "2006" ;
  schema:publisher "Social Anthropology" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/K8SXMRBB>
  a schema:Book ;
  schema:name "The Cooking of History: How Not to Study Afro-Cuban Religion" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=K8SXMRBB> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:K8SXMRBB" ;
  schema:description "Over a lifetime of studying Cuban Santería and other religions related to Orisha worship—a practice also found among the Yoruba in West Africa—Stephan Palmié has grown progressively uneasy with the assumptions inherent in the very term Afro-Cuban religion. In The Cooking of History he provides a comprehensive analysis of these assumptions, in the process offering an incisive critique both of the anthropology of religion and of scholarship on the cultural history of the Afro-Atlantic World. Under" ;
  schema:author "Palmié, Stephan" ;
  schema:datePublished "2013" ;
  schema:publisher "University Of Chicago Press" ;
  dcterms:identifier "isbn:0-226-01956-X" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/35TPVIXL>
  a schema:Thesis ;
  schema:name "Liberating the family? Gender, labor, and sexuality in the rural Western Cape, South Africa, 1823-1853. (Volumes I and II)." ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=35TPVIXL> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:35TPVIXL" ;
  schema:description "The dissertation argues that gender ideologies and practices critically informed slave emancipation in the British Empire. Using official correspondence, court records, missionary journals, and marriage records I focus on the period of amelioration, emancipation, and postemancipation in the rural Western Cape Colony up to the granting of Representative Government in 1853. I analyze how slaves, dependent laborers, slaveholders, missionaries, and officials conceptualized gender relations, the relationship between labor and family, and the meanings of freedom. Legislation ameliorating slavery in the 1820s and 1830s focused on relations within the slave family and represented slave women as requiring special protection in the workplace. In the apprenticeship period from 1834 to 1838 apprentice women became spokespeople in the battle over child labor which was a prime site of struggle in the transition to a wage labor economy. Relationships formed under slavery influenced whether freed people moved to missions or villages or remained on the farms after 1838. Freed people participated in a family economy in which women, men, and children contributed in different ways to the household. Law also framed the worlds of labor. Labor legislation consolidated the conception of women as belonging to a special category of worker by allowing their dismissal should they get married or become pregnant. Slave emancipation produced a preoccupation with cultural categories and sensibility. Freed people of all stations of life married in small numbers after emancipation, partly to signify freedom from slavery. In the 1840s state officials represented women charged with infanticide on the missions as victims of excessive missionary moral zeal. This facilitated the state's aim to limit the power of missionaries over the freed population, and silenced women's claims that patriarchal social relations had contributed to their actions. Finally, analysis of rape cases show that while black women took men to court throughout the postemancipation period judicial decisions were premised upon a belief that black women had no honor to lose. Postemancipation colonial culture was premised on implicit yet powerful connections between race, gender, and authority." ;
  schema:author "Pamela Scully" ;
  schema:datePublished "1993" ;
  schema:publisher "Deep Blue (University of Michigan)" ;
  dcterms:subject "South African History and Culture" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/ANGVWVR7>
  a schema:Chapter ;
  schema:name "Text-Based Emergency Alert Framework for Under-Resourced Languages in Southern Nigeria" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=ANGVWVR7> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:ANGVWVR7" ;
  schema:description "Computational techniques are today bridging communication gap between speakers of different languages through natural language processing (NLP) techniques leading to the current description of the world as a global village. While languages like English, French, Mandarin, Spanish, and Russian, etc., are now easily translated to each other, most native African languages have not witnessed any such automated efforts toward translation to ease communication and information sharing between native speakers and non-speakers. Africa's language diversity is second to none on the planet. Under-resourced Nigerian languages, like Ibibio, Ijaw, Oro, Itshekiri, etc., if automated, could result in discovery of far-reaching knowledge and information. Under-resourced Nigerian languages lack lexical corpora or trained models for NLP tasks. Meeting the need for automated under-resourced language translation requires development of new techniques and expansion of existing machine-driven local language translation tools. Thus, this work proposes the use of a hybrid translation method incorporating rule-based and corpus-based translation approaches. This would result in creation of multilingual framework for automatic machine translation of English to Ibibio, an under-resourced language spoken in southern Nigeria and vice versa. The framework and the resulting Ibibio bilingual application programming interface (API) will drive the generation of multilingual emergency alert system across Southern Nigeria." ;
  schema:author "Patience U. Usip" ;
  schema:creator "Funebi Francis Ijebu", "Ifiok J. Udo", "Ikechukwu K. Ollawa" ;
  schema:datePublished "2023" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.1201/9781003313267-5> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.1201/9781003313267-5" ;
  dcterms:subject "Natural Language Processing Techniques", "Speech and dialogue systems" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/JWRRVNIB>
  a schema:Thesis ;
  schema:name "Slave Legacies, Ambivalent Modernity: Street Commerce and the Transition to Free Labor in Rio de Janeiro, 1850-1925" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=JWRRVNIB> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:JWRRVNIB" ;
  schema:description "\"Slave Legacies, Ambivalent Modernity: Street Commerce and the Transition to Free Labor in Rio de Janeiro, 1850-1925\" is a history of street vending during the transition from enslaved to free labor in the capital of the most enduring slave society of the Americas. Street vending - long the province of African slaves and free blacks - became in these years a site of expanded (European) immigrant participation and shifting state disciplinary policies. My dissertation contends that during the gradual transition to free labor, urban policing and the judicial system in the city of Rio came to target \"criminality\" rather than illicit or improper vending practices. Disciplinary measures established by criminal law focused on correcting individuals who were peddlers and not inadequately regulated street commercial activity. Thus, the language of citizenship appeared in court cases to both establish and resist negative characterizations of street vendors while a gradual marginalization of street commerce occurred within the framework of citizenship building. The practice of street commerce during this transitional era reveals a historical process that produced and transformed notions of legitimate work and public order as well as the racial segmentation of the labor force. Street vending, I argue, became a strategy of subsistence among the post-abolition urban poor, who came to their own understandings of freedom, free labor, and citizenship. Elite and popular attitudes toward street vending reflected the post-abolition political economy of exclusion and inclusion, which peddlers did not experience as mutually exclusive but rather as a dialectic of an ambivalent modernity." ;
  schema:author "Patricia Acerbi" ;
  schema:datePublished "2010" ;
  schema:publisher "Digital Repository at the University of Maryland (University of Maryland College Park)" ;
  dcterms:subject "Colonialism, slavery, and trade" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/TJWRSXBP>
  a schema:Thesis ;
  schema:name "A collection of discrete essays with the common theme of gender and slavery at the Cape of Good Hope with a focus on the 1820s" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=TJWRSXBP> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:TJWRSXBP" ;
  schema:description "This is a collection of discrete essays, each embodying original research and bearing on the theme of gender and slavery at the Cape of Good Hope. Amelioration at the Cape profoundly altered gendered perceptions of slaves, both on the part of slaveholders, and of the slaves themselves. The amelioration regulations entailed a redefinition of the gender of female slaves, which was resisted by slaveholders and transformed by slave women, while slave men began to redefine their own gendered identities in this light. Slaveholders' traditional patriarchal self-concepts were severely threatened in this context, as they progressively lost power and authority, both to the new paternalist colonial state and to those who had formerly been subsumed within the patriarchal family. There are five papers, the first an introduction to the theoretical framework of the collection and an outline of the general argument as outlined above. The second paper provides a critique of existing Cape slave historiography from a gendered perspective. It examines the problems of this literature methodologically and theoretically, focusing on the implications of the slave sex ratio for the history of slave women. The final three papers are based on empirical research. The third paper examines the structural constraints on slave family formation in Cape Town from the perspective of slave women. The fourth and fifth papers explore issues related to infanticide and slave reproduction, and slave resistance in relation to the Bokkeveld rebellion of 1825, respectively." ;
  schema:author "Patricia van der Spuy" ;
  schema:datePublished "1993" ;
  schema:publisher "Open University of Cape Town (University of Cape Town)" ;
  dcterms:subject "African history and culture studies", "Colonialism, slavery, and trade", "Global Maritime and Colonial Histories" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/BTZWVWHQ>
  a schema:Thesis ;
  schema:name "Natural Law, Literary Accommodation and the Successful Social Justice Movement : Thomas Reid's Natural Law Philosophy and the Abolitionist Writings of Olaudah Equiano and Ottobah Cugoano" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=BTZWVWHQ> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:BTZWVWHQ" ;
  schema:description "I will be discussing natural law and the abolition movement of the 18th century-specifically the works of Olaudah Equiano and Ottobah Cugoano, two freed slaves who were members of an English abolitionist society known as the Sons of Africa- and the role that Scottish philosopher Thomas Reid’s ideas of natural law played in their authorship. Natural law philosophy, based on the idea that observation of the natural world can lead to conclusions about morality, has largely been sidelined in modern conversations about ethics. However, it played an important part in one of the greatest moral struggles of western society- the abolition of slavery- both by producing a coherent set of arguments against the practice and, as I will argue, promoting a method of communication by which those arguments were to be successfully delivered. In this project I will seek to demonstrate how natural law philosophy lead early abolitionists to prioritize a literary style that seeks common ground on a basis of universal human identity." ;
  schema:author "Patrick D. Miller" ;
  schema:datePublished "2020" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.32597/honors/238/> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.32597/honors/238/" ;
  dcterms:subject "Law in Society and Culture", "Legal principles and applications", "Multicultural Socio-Legal Studies" .

<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/VZT6XS4Z>
  a schema:Thesis ;
  schema:name "Urban slavery in the Southwest" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=VZT6XS4Z> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
